  30class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  31    """
  32    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  33    provided by that function.
  34    
  35    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  36    """
  37    _iter: SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]
  38
  39    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T]) -> None:
  40        super().__init__()
  41        self._iter = SequenceTransform(iterable)
  42
  43    @overload
  44    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  45        ...
  46    @overload
  47    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:

  49    @overload
  50    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  51        ...
  52    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  53        """
  54        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
  55
  56        Example 1:
  57        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  58        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
  59        ['a1', 'a2']
  60
  61        Example 2:
  62        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  63        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
  64        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
  65        """
  66        return FilteringTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)).as_sequence()
  67
  68    @deprecated("use `.filter(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.", category=None)
  69    def filter_indexed(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  70        return self.filter(predicate)
  71
  72    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
  73        """
  74        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
  75
  76        Example 1:
  77        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
  78        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
  79        [1, 3]
  80
  81        """
  82        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ)) # type: ignore

  85    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  86        ...
  87    @overload
  88    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  89        ...
  90    @overload
  91    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  92        ...
  93    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  94        """
  95        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
  96
  97        Example 1:
  98        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  99        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 100        ['b1', 'b2']
 101
 102        Example 2:
 103        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 104        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 105        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 106        """
 107        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 108        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))

 111    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:

 114    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
 115        ...
 116    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 117        """
 118        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are not `None`.
 119
 120        Example 1:
 121        >>> lst = [ 'a', None, 'b']
 122        >>> it(lst).filter_not_none().to_list()
 123        ['a', 'b']
 124        """
 125        return self.filter(lambda x: x is not None) # type: ignore

 133    @overload
 134    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 135        ...
 136    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 137        """
 138        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 139        to each element in the original Sequence.
 140
 141        Example 1:
 142        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 143        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 144        [12, 13]
 145
 146        Example 2:
 147        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 148        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 149        ['A0', 'B1']
 150
 151        Example 3:
 152        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 153        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 154        [2, 3]
 155        """
 156        return MappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)).as_sequence()
 157    
 158    @deprecated("use `.map(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.", category=None)
 159    def map_indexed(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 160        return self.map(transform)

 164    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[[T], Awaitable[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:

 166    @overload
 167    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], Awaitable[R]], return_exceptions: Literal[True]) -> Sequence[Union[R, BaseException]]:
 168        ...
 169    @overload
 170    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Awaitable[R]], return_exceptions: Literal[False] = False) -> Sequence[R]:
 171        ...
 172    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[..., Awaitable[R]], return_exceptions: bool = False):
 173        """
 174        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 175        """
 176        from asyncio import gather
 177        if return_exceptions:
 178            return it(await gather(*self.map(transform), return_exceptions=True))
 179        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform)))

 182    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:

 188    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:

 190    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[..., Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 191        """
 192        Returns a Sequence containing only the non-none results of applying the given [transform] function
 193        to each element in the original collection.
 194
 195        Example 1:
 196        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 197        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 198        [12]
 199        """
 200        return self.map(transform).filter_not_none() # type: ignore

 208    @overload
 209    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 210        ...
 211    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[..., R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 212        """
 213        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 214        to each element in the original Sequence.
 215
 216        Example 1:
 217        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 218        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 219        [12, 13]
 220
 221        Example 2:
 222        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 223        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age'], max_workers=2).to_list()
 224        [12, 13]
 225
 226        Example 3:
 227        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 228        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x, i: x['age'] + i, max_workers=2).to_list()
 229        [12, 14]
 230        """
 231        return ParallelMappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform), max_workers, chunksize, executor).as_sequence()

 241        ...
 242    def find(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 243        """
 244        Returns the first element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 245        
 246        Example 1:
 247        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 248        >>> it(lst).find(lambda x: x == 'b')
 249        'b'
 250        """
 251        return self.first_or_none(predicate)
 252    
 253    def find_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 254        """
 255        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 256        
 257        Example 1:
 258        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 259        >>> it(lst).find_last(lambda x: x == 'b')
 260        'b'
 261        """
 262        return self.last_or_none(predicate)

 264    @overload

 273    @overload
 274    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 275        ...
 276    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 277        """
 278        Returns first element.
 279
 280        Example 1:
 281        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 282        >>> it(lst).first()
 283        'a'
 284
 285        Example 2:
 286        >>> lst = []
 287        >>> it(lst).first()
 288        Traceback (most recent call last):
 289        ...
 290        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 291
 292        Example 3:
 293        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 294        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 295        'b'
 296
 297        Example 4:
 298        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 299        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 300        Traceback (most recent call last):
 301        ...
 302        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 303
 304        Example 5:
 305        >>> lst = [None]
 306        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 307        True
 308        """
 309        for e in self:
 310            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 311                return e
 312        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")
 313
 314    @overload

 323    @overload
 324    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Callable[[Optional[R], int, Sequence[Optional[R]]], Optional[R]]) -> R:
 325        ...
 326    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[R]]] = None) -> R:
 327        """
 328        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 329
 330        Example 1:
 331        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 332        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 333        12
 334
 335        Example 2:
 336        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 337        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 338        Traceback (most recent call last):
 339        ...
 340        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 341        """
 342
 343        v = self.first_not_none_of_or_none() if transform is None else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 344        if v is None:
 345            raise ValueError('No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.')
 346        return v

 359        ...
 360    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 361        """
 362        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 363
 364        Example 1:
 365        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 366        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 367        12
 368
 369        Example 2:
 370        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 371        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 372        True
 373        """
 374        if transform is None:
 375            return self.first_or_none()
 376        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 389        ...
 390    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 391        """
 392        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 393
 394        Example 1:
 395        >>> lst = []
 396        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 397        True
 398
 399        Example 2:
 400        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 401        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 402        'a'
 403
 404        Example 2:
 405        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 406        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 407        'b'
 408        """
 409        return next(iter(self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate)), None)

 412    @overload
 413    def first_or_default(self, default: T) -> T :
 414        ...
 415    @overload
 416    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool], default: T) -> T :

 418    @overload
 419    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool], default: T) -> T :
 420        ...
 421    @overload
 422    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool], default: T) -> T :
 423        ...
 424    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], T], default: Optional[T] = None) -> T: # type: ignore
 425        """
 426        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 427
 428        Example 1:
 429        >>> lst = []
 430        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 431        'a'
 432
 433        Example 2:
 434        >>> lst = ['b']
 435        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 436        'b'
 437        
 438        Example 3:
 439        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 440        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 441        'b'
 442
 443        Example 4:
 444        >>> lst = []
 445        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 446        'd'
 447        """
 448        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 449            return none_or(self.first_or_none(predicate), default) # type: ignore
 450        else:
 451            default = predicate
 452        return none_or(self.first_or_none(), default)
 453
 454    @overload
 455    def last(self) -> T:
 456        ...

 463    @overload
 464    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 465        ...
 466    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 467        """
 468        Returns last element.
 469
 470        Example 1:
 471        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 472        >>> it(lst).last()
 473        'c'
 474
 475        Example 2:
 476        >>> lst = []
 477        >>> it(lst).last()
 478        Traceback (most recent call last):
 479        ...
 480        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 481        """
 482        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 483        if v is None:
 484            raise ValueError('Sequence is empty.')
 485        return v
 486
 487    @overload
 488    def last_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 489        ...
 490    @overload
 491    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 492        ...
 493    @overload
 494    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 495        ...
 496    @overload
 497    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 498        ...
 499    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 500        """
 501        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 502
 503        Exmaple 1:
 504        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 505        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 506        'c'
 507
 508        Exmaple 2:
 509        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 510        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 511        'b'
 512
 513        Exmaple 3:
 514        >>> lst = []
 515        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 516        True
 517        """
 518        last: Optional[T] = None
 519        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 520            last = i
 521        return last
 522    
 523    def index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 524        """
 525        Returns first index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 526
 527        Example 1:
 528        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 529        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('b')
 530        1
 531
 532        Example 2:
 533        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 534        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('d')
 535        """
 536        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 537            if x == element:
 538                return i
 539        return None
 540
 541    def index_of(self, element: T) -> int:
 542        """
 543        Returns first index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.
 544         
 545        Example 1:
 546        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 547        >>> it(lst).index_of('b')
 548        1
 549
 550        Example 2:
 551        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 552        >>> it(lst).index_of('d')
 553        -1
 554        """
 555        return none_or(self.index_of_or_none(element), -1)
 556

 573    def index_of_or_else(self, element: T, f: Callable[[], int]) -> int:
 574        """
 575        Returns first index of [element], or computes the value from a callback if the collection does not contain element.
 576         
 577        Example 1:
 578        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 579        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_else('b', lambda: 2)
 580        1
 581
 582        Example 2:
 583        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 584        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_else('d', lambda: 0)
 585        0
 586        """

 588    
 589    def last_index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 590        """
 591         Returns last index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 592
 593        Example 1:
 594        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 595        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('b')
 596        3
 597
 598        Example 2:
 599        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 600        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('d')
 601        """
 602        seq = self.reversed()
 603        last_idx = len(seq) - 1
 604        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 605            if x == element:
 606                return last_idx - i
 607        return None

 666    def index_of_first_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Optional[int]:
 667        """
 668        Returns first index of element matching the given [predicate], or None if no such element was found.
 669
 670        Example 1:
 671        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 672        >>> it(lst).index_of_first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')

 679        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 680        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 681            if predicate(x):
 682                return i
 683        return None

 903        ...
 904    @overload
 905    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 906        ...
 907    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 908        """
 909        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
 910        or more than one matching element.
 911
 912        Exmaple 1:
 913        >>> lst = ['a']
 914        >>> it(lst).single()
 915        'a'
 916
 917        Exmaple 2:
 918        >>> lst = []
 919        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 920        Traceback (most recent call last):
 921        ...
 922        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
 923
 924        Exmaple 2:
 925        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 926        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 927        Traceback (most recent call last):
 928        ...
 929        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
 930        """
 931        single: Optional[T] = None
 932        found = False
 933        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 934            if found:
 935                raise ValueError('Sequence contains more than one matching element.')
 936            single = i
 937            found = True
 938        if single is None:
 939            raise ValueError('Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.')
 940        return single
 941
 942    @overload
 943    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 944        ...
 945    @overload
 946    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 947        ...
 948    @overload
 949    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 950        ...
 951    @overload
 952    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 953        ...
 954    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 955        """
 956        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
 957        or more than one element was found.
 958
 959        Exmaple 1:
 960        >>> lst = ['a']
 961        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 962        'a'
 963
 964        Exmaple 2:
 965        >>> lst = []
 966        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 967
 968        Exmaple 2:
 969        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 970        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 971
 972        """
 973        single: Optional[T] = None
 974        found = False
 975        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 976            if found:
 977                return None
 978            single = i
 979            found = True
 980        if not found:
 981            return None
 982        return single
 983
 984    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
 985    def drop(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
 986        """
 987        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first [n] elements.
 988
 989        Example 1:
 990        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 991        >>> it(lst).drop(0).to_list()
 992        ['a', 'b', 'c']
 993
 994        Example 2:
 995        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 996        >>> it(lst).drop(1).to_list()
 997        ['b', 'c']
 998
 999        Example 2:
1000        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1001        >>> it(lst).drop(4).to_list()
1002        []
1003        """
1004        if n < 0:
1005            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
1006        if n == 0:
1007            return self
1008
1009        return DropTransform(self, n).as_sequence()

1027        >>> it(lst).drop_while(lambda x: x < 3 ).to_list()

1029        """

1074    def take(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1075        """
1076        Returns an Sequence containing first [n] elements.
1077
1078        Example 1:
1079        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1080        >>> it(a).take(0).to_list()
1081        []
1082
1083        Example 2:
1084        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1085        >>> it(a).take(2).to_list()
1086        ['a', 'b']
1087        """
1088        if n < 0:
1089            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
1090        if n == 0:
1091            return Sequence([])
1092        return TakeTransform(self, n).as_sequence()

1106        Returns an Sequence containing first elements satisfying the given [predicate].
1107

1110        >>> it(lst).take_while(lambda x: x in ['a', 'b']).to_list()

1115    def take_last(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1116        """
1117        Returns an Sequence containing last [n] elements.
1118
1119        Example 1:
1120        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1121        >>> it(a).take_last(0).to_list()
1122        []
1123
1124        Example 2:
1125        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1126        >>> it(a).take_last(2).to_list()
1127        ['b', 'c']
1128        """
1129        if n < 0:
1130            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
1131        if n == 0:
1132            return Sequence([])
1133
1134        return self.drop(len(self) - n)

1136    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1137    def sorted(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1138        """
1139        Returns an Sequence that yields elements of this Sequence sorted according to their natural sort order.
1140
1141        Example 1:
1142        >>> lst = ['b', 'a', 'e', 'c']
1143        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
1144        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'e']
1145
1146         Example 2:
1147        >>> lst = [2, 1, 4, 3]
1148        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
1149        [1, 2, 3, 4]
1150        """
1151        lst = list(self)
1152        lst.sort() # type: ignore
1153        return it(lst)

1164        ...
1165    def sorted_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., SupportsRichComparisonT]) -> Sequence[T]:
1166        """
1167        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to natural sort
1168        order of the value returned by specified [key_selector] function.
1169
1170        Example 1:
1171        >>> lst = [ {'name': 'A', 'age': 12 }, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10 }, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11 } ]
1172        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['name']).to_list()
1173        [{'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10}]
1174        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
1175        [{'name': 'C', 'age': 10}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'A', 'age': 12}]
1176        """
1177        lst = list(self)
1178        lst.sort(key=self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector))
1179        return it(lst)

1181    def sorted_descending(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1182        """
1183        Returns a Sequence of all elements sorted descending according to their natural sort order.
1184
1185        Example 1:
1186        >>> lst = ['b', 'c', 'a']
1187        >>> it(lst).sorted_descending().to_list()
1188        ['c', 'b', 'a']
1189        """
1190        return self.sorted().reversed()

1201    def sorted_by_descending(self, key_selector: Callable[..., SupportsRichComparisonT]) -> Sequence[T]:
1202        """
1203        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted descending according
1204        to natural sort order of the value returned by specified [key_selector] function.
1205
1206        Example 1:
1207        >>> lst = [ {'name': 'A', 'age': 12 }, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10 }, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11 } ]
1208        >>> it(lst).sorted_by_descending(lambda x: x['name']).to_list()
1209        [{'name': 'C', 'age': 10}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'A', 'age': 12}]
1210        >>> it(lst).sorted_by_descending(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
1211        [{'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10}]
1212        """
1213        return self.sorted_by(key_selector).reversed()

1215    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1216    def sorted_with(self, comparator: Callable[[T, T], int]) -> Sequence[T]:
1217        """
1218        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to the specified [comparator].
1219
1220        Example 1:
1221        >>> lst = ['aa', 'bbb', 'c']
1222        >>> it(lst).sorted_with(lambda a, b: len(a)-len(b)).to_list()
1223        ['c', 'aa', 'bbb']
1224        """
1225        from functools import cmp_to_key
1226        lst = list(self)
1227        lst.sort(key=cmp_to_key(comparator))
1228        return it(lst)

1239    def associate(self, transform: Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]) -> Dict[K, V]:
1240        """
1241        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
1242        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
1243
1244        Example 1:
1245        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
1246        >>> it(lst).associate(lambda x: (int(x), x))
1247        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
1248        """
1249        transform = self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)
1250        dic: Dict[K, V] = dict()
1251        for i in self:
1252            k, v = transform(i)
1253            dic[k] = v
1254        return dic

1269                     value_transform: Optional[Callable[[T], V]] = None) -> Union[Dict[K, T], Dict[K, V]]:
1270        """
1271        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
1272        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
1273

1285        key_selector = self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector)

1289            k = key_selector(i)
1290            dic[k] = i if value_transform is None else value_transform(i)

1331        """
1332        Returns True if all elements of the Sequence satisfy the specified [predicate] function.
1333
1334        Example 1:
1335        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1336        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 0)
1337        True
1338        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 1)
1339        False
1340        """
1341        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1342        for i in self:
1343            if not predicate(i):
1344                return False
1345        return True

1384        ...
1385    def count(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> int:
1386        """
1387        Returns the number of elements in the Sequence that satisfy the specified [predicate] function.
1388
1389        Example 1:
1390        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1391        >>> it(lst).count()
1392        3
1393        >>> it(lst).count(lambda x: x > 0)
1394        3
1395        >>> it(lst).count(lambda x: x > 2)
1396        1
1397        """
1398        if predicate is None:
1399            return len(self)
1400        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1401        return sum(1 for i in self if predicate(i))

1417    def element_at(self, index: int) -> T:
1418        """
1419        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence.

1422        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]

1429        Traceback (most recent call last):
1430        ...
1431        IndexError: Index 3 out of range
1432        """
1433        return self.element_at_or_else(index, lambda index: throw(IndexError(f'Index {index} out of range')))

1450    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: None) -> Optional[T]:
1451        ...
1452    @overload
1453    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: Callable[[int], T]) -> T:
1454        ...
1455    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: Union[Callable[[int], T], T, None]) -> Union[Optional[T], T]:
1456        """
1457        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or the [default] value if the index is out of bounds.
1458
1459        Example 1:
1460        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1461        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(1, lambda x: 'default')
1462        2
1463        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(4, lambda x: 'default')
1464        'default'
1465
1466        """
1467        if (index < 0):
1468            return default(index) if callable(default) else default
1469        
1470        if type(self._iter) == SequenceTransform and isinstance(self._iter._iter, list) and index < len(self._iter._iter): # type: ignore
1471            return self._iter._iter[index] # type: ignore
1472        for i, e in enumerate(self):
1473            if i == index:
1474                return e
1475        return default(index) if callable(default) else default
1476

1485        2
1486        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_default(4, 'default')
1487        'default'
1488
1489        """
1490        return self.element_at_or_else(index, default)

1506    def distinct(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1507        """
1508        Returns a new Sequence containing the distinct elements of the given Sequence.
1509
1510        Example 1:
1511        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3]
1512        >>> it(lst).distinct().to_list()
1513        [1, 2, 3]
1514
1515        Example 2:
1516        >>> lst = [(1, 'A'), (1, 'A'), (1, 'A'), (2, 'A'), (3, 'C'), (3, 'D')]
1517        >>> it(lst).distinct().sorted().to_list()
1518        [(1, 'A'), (2, 'A'), (3, 'C'), (3, 'D')]
1519
1520        """
1521        return DistinctTransform(self).as_sequence()

1543    @overload
1544    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[T, T], T]) -> T:
1545        ...
1546    @overload
1547    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[R, T], R], initial: R) -> R:
1548        ...
1549    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[..., R], initial: Optional[R] = None) -> Optional[R]:
1550        """
1551        Returns the result of applying the specified [accumulator] function to the given Sequence's elements.
1552
1553        Example 1:
1554        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1555        >>> it(lst).reduce(lambda x, y: x+y)
1556        6
1557        """
1558        result: Optional[R] = initial
1559        for i, e in enumerate(self):
1560            if i == 0 and initial is None:
1561                result = e # type: ignore
1562                continue
1563            
1564            result = accumulator(result, e)
1565        return result
1566

1575        """
1576        return self.reduce(accumulator, initial)

1618    def max_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], Union[float, int]]) -> Optional[T]:
1619        """
1620        Returns the first element yielding the largest value of the given function
1621        or `none` if there are no elements.
1622
1623        Example 1:
1624        >>> lst = [ { "name": "A", "num": 100 }, { "name": "B", "num": 200 }]
1625        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1626        {'name': 'B', 'num': 200}
1627
1628        Example 2:
1629        >>> lst = []
1630        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1631        """
1632
1633        max_item = None
1634        max_val = None
1635
1636        for item in self:
1637            val = selector(item)
1638            if max_val is None or val > max_val:
1639                max_item = item
1640                max_val = val
1641        
1642        return max_item

1753        Example 1:
1754        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1755        >>> it(lst).mean_of(lambda x: x)
1756        2.0
1757        """
1758        return self.sum_of(selector) / len(self)

1908    def group_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., K]) -> Sequence[Grouping[K, T]]:
1909        """
1910        Returns a dictionary with keys being the result of [key_selector] function being invoked on each element of original collection
1911        and values being the corresponding elements of original collection.
1912
1913        Example 1:

1915        >>> it(lst).group_by(lambda x: x%2).map(lambda x: (x.key, x.values.to_list())).to_list()

1917        """
1918        return GroupingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector)).as_sequence()

1921    def group_by_to(self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[[T], K]) -> Dict[K, List[T]]:
1922        ...

1924    def group_by_to(self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[[T, int], K]) -> Dict[K, List[T]]:
1925        ...

1927    def group_by_to(self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], K]) -> Dict[K, List[T]]:
1928        ...
1929    def group_by_to(self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[..., K]) -> Dict[K, List[T]]:
1930        """
1931        Returns a dictionary with keys being the result of [key_selector] function being invoked on each element of original collection
1932        and values being the corresponding elements of original collection.
1933
1934        Example 1:
1935        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
1936        >>> it(lst).group_by_to({}, lambda x: x%2)
1937        {1: [1, 3, 5], 0: [2, 4]}
1938        """
1939        key_selector = self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector)
1940        for e in self:
1941            k = key_selector(e)
1942            if k not in destination:
1943                destination[k] = []
1944            destination[k].append(e)
1945        return destination

2018    def on_each(self, action: Callable[..., None]) -> Sequence[T]:
2019        """
2020        Invokes [action] function on each element of the given Sequence.
2021
2022        Example 1:
2023        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2024        >>> it(lst).on_each(lambda x: print(x)) and None
2025        a
2026        b
2027        c
2028
2029        Example 2:
2030        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2031        >>> it(lst).on_each(lambda x, i: print(x, i)) and None
2032        a 0
2033        b 1
2034        c 2
2035        """
2036        action = self._callback_overload_warpper(action)
2037        for i in self:
2038            action(i)
2039        return self

2084    def zip(self, other: Iterable[Any], transform: Optional[Callable[..., Any]] = None) -> Sequence[Any]:
2085        """
2086        Returns a new Sequence of tuples, where each tuple contains two elements.
2087        
2088        Example 1:
2089        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2090        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2091        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2).to_list()
2092        [('a', 1), ('b', 2), ('c', 3)]
2093
2094        Example 2:
2095        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2096        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2097        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2, lambda x, y: x + '__' +str( y)).to_list()
2098        ['a__1', 'b__2', 'c__3']
2099        """
2100        if transform is None:
2101            transform = lambda *x:(*x,)
2102        return MergingTransform(self, other, transform).as_sequence()

2151        ...
2152    def unzip(self, transform: Union[Optional[Callable[..., Tuple[Any, Any]]], bool]=None, as_sequence: bool=False) -> Any: # type: ignore
2153        """
2154        Returns a pair of lists, where first list is built from the first values of each pair from this array, second list is built from the second values of each pair from this array.
2155
2156        Example 1:
2157        >>> lst = [{'name': 'a', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'b', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'c', 'age': 13}]
2158        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip(lambda x: (x['name'], x['age']))
2159        >>> a
2160        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2161        >>> b
2162        [11, 12, 13]
2163        
2164        Example 1:
2165        >>> lst = [('a', 11), ('b', 12), ('c', 13)]
2166        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip()
2167        >>> a
2168        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2169        >>> b
2170        [11, 12, 13]
2171        """
2172        it = self
2173        if isinstance(transform, bool):
2174            as_sequence = transform
2175            transform = None
2176
2177        if transform is not None:
2178            transform = self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)
2179            it = it.map(transform)
2180        
2181        a = it.map(lambda x: x[0]) # type: ignore
2182        b = it.map(lambda x: x[1]) # type: ignore
2183
2184        if not as_sequence:
2185            return a.to_list(), b.to_list()
2186        return a, b
2187

2256        ...
2257    def partition(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool], as_sequence: bool=False):
2258        """
2259        Partitions the elements of the given Sequence into two groups,
2260        the first group containing the elements for which the predicate returns true,
2261        and the second containing the rest.
2262
2263        Example 1:
2264        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
2265        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda x: x.isalpha())
2266        (['a', 'b', 'c'], ['2'])
2267
2268        Example 2:
2269        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
2270        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda _, i: i % 2 == 0)
2271        (['a', 'c'], ['b', '2'])
2272        """
2273        predicate_a = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
2274        predicate_b = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
2275        part_a = self.filter(predicate_a)
2276        part_b = self.filter(lambda x: not predicate_b(x))
2277        if not as_sequence:
2278            return part_a.to_list(), part_b.to_list()
2279        return part_a, part_b 
2280

2331    def windowed(self, size: int, step: int = 1, partialWindows: bool = False) -> Sequence[List[T]]:
2332        """
2333         Returns a Sequence of all possible sliding windows of size [size] from the given Sequence.
2334
2335        Example 1:
2336        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']
2337        >>> it(lst).windowed(3).to_list()
2338        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['b', 'c', 'd'], ['c', 'd', 'e']]
2339
2340        Example 2:
2341        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']
2342        >>> it(lst).windowed(3, 2).to_list()
2343        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['c', 'd', 'e']]
2344
2345        Example 3:
2346        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']
2347        >>> it(lst).windowed(3, 2, True).to_list()
2348        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['c', 'd', 'e'], ['e', 'f']]
2349        """
2350        return WindowedTransform(self, size, step, partialWindows).as_sequence()
2351    
2352
2353    def chunked(self, size: int) -> Sequence[List[T]]:
2354        """
2355        Returns a Sequence of all possible chunks of size [size] from the given Sequence.
2356
2357        Example 1:
2358        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']
2359        >>> it(lst).chunked(3).to_list()
2360        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d', 'e']]
2361
2362
2363        Example 2:
2364        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']
2365        >>> it(lst).chunked(3).to_list()
2366        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d', 'e', 'f']]
2367        """
2368        return self.windowed(size, size, True)
2369
2370    def repeat(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
2371        """
2372        Returns a Sequence containing this sequence repeated n times.
2373
2374        Example 1:
2375        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
2376        >>> it(lst).repeat(3).to_list()
2377        ['a', 'b', 'a', 'b', 'a', 'b']
2378        """
2379
2380        return ConcatTransform([self] * n).as_sequence()
2381    
2382    def concat(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2383        """
2384        Returns a Sequence of all elements of the given Sequence, followed by all elements of the given Sequence.
2385
2386        Example 1:
2387        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2388        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2389        >>> it(lst1).concat(lst2).to_list()
2390        ['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3]
2391
2392        Example 2:
2393        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2394        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2395        >>> lst3 = [4, 5, 6]
2396        >>> it(lst1).concat(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2397        ['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
2398        """
2399        return ConcatTransform([self, *other]).as_sequence()
2400    
2401    def intersect(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2402        """
2403        Returns a set containing all elements that are contained by both this collection and the specified collection.
2404
2405        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection.
2406
2407        To get a set containing all elements that are contained at least in one of these collections use union.
2408
2409        Example 1:
2410        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2411        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2412        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2413        ['c']
2414
2415        Example 2:
2416        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2417        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2418        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2419        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2420        ['b']
2421
2422
2423        Example 1:
2424        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2425        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2426        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2427        ['a']
2428        """
2429        return IntersectionTransform([self, *other]).as_sequence()
2430    
2431    def union(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2432        """
2433        Returns a set containing all distinct elements from both collections.
2434
2435        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection. Those elements of the other collection that are unique are iterated in the end in the order of the other collection.
2436
2437        To get a set containing all elements that are contained in both collections use intersect.
2438
2439        Example 1:
2440        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2441        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2442        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2443        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2444
2445        Example 2:
2446        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2447        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2448        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2449        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2450        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'a3', 'c3']
2451
2452
2453        Example 1:
2454        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2455        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2456        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2457        ['a', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2458        """
2459        return self.concat(*other).distinct()
2460    
2461
2462    def join(self: Sequence[str], separator: str = ' ') -> str:
2463        """
2464        Joins the elements of the given Sequence into a string.
2465
2466        Example 1:
2467        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2468        >>> it(lst).join(', ')
2469        'a, b, c'
2470        """
2471        return separator.join(self)

2473    @overload
2474    def progress(self) -> Sequence[T]:
2475        ...
2476    @overload
2477    def progress(self, progress_func: Union[Literal['tqdm'], Literal['tqdm_rich']]) -> Sequence[T]:
2478        ...
2479    @overload
2480    def progress(self, progress_func: Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]]) -> Sequence[T]:
2481        ...
2482    def progress(self, progress_func: Union[Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]], Literal['tqdm'], Literal['tqdm_rich'], None ] = None) -> Sequence[T]:
2483        """
2484        Returns a Sequence that enable a progress bar for the given Sequence.
2485        
2486        Example 1:
2487        >>> from tqdm import tqdm
2488        >>> from time import sleep
2489        >>> it(range(10)).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).parallel_map(lambda x: sleep(0.), max_workers=5).to_list() and None
2490        >>> for _ in it(list(range(10))).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).to_list(): pass
2491        """
2492        if progress_func is not None and callable(progress_func):
2493            return ProgressTransform(self, progress_func).as_sequence()
2494        
2495        def import_tqdm():
2496            if progress_func == 'tqdm_rich':
2497                from tqdm.rich import tqdm
2498            else:
2499                from tqdm import tqdm
2500            return tqdm
2501
2502        try:
2503            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2504        except ImportError:
2505            from pip import main as pip
2506            pip(['install', 'tqdm'])
2507            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2508        
2509        return it(tqdm(self, total=len(self)))

2512    def typing_as(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
2513        """
2514        Cast the element as specific Type to gain code completion base on type annotations.
2515        """
2516        el = self.first_not_none_of_or_none()
2517        if el is None or isinstance(el, typ) or not isinstance(el, dict):
2518            return self # type: ignore
2519
2520        class AttrDict(Dict[str, Any]):
2521            def __init__(self, value: Dict[str, Any]) -> None:
2522                super().__init__(**value)
2523                setattr(self, '__dict__', value)
2524                self.__getattr__  = value.__getitem__
2525                self.__setattr__ = value.__setattr__ # type: ignore
2526        return self.map(AttrDict) # type: ignore  # use https://github.com/cdgriffith/Box ?

2551    def to_dict(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]]=None) -> Dict[K, V]:
2552        """
2553        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
2554        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
2555
2556        Example 1:
2557        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
2558        >>> it(lst).to_dict(lambda x: (int(x), x))
2559        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
2560
2561        Example 2:
2562        >>> lst = [(1, '1'), (2, '2'), (3, '3')]
2563        >>> it(lst).to_dict()
2564        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
2565        """
2566        return self.associate(transform or (lambda x: x)) # type: ignore

2589    def let(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], R]) -> R:
2590        """
2591        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns its result.
2592            
2593        Example 1:
2594        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).let(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()
2595        ['a!', 'b!', 'c!']

2597        return block(self)

2599    def also(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], Any]) -> Sequence[T]:
2600        """
2601        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns `self` value.
2602            
2603        Example 1:
2604        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).also(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()
2605        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2606        """
2607        block(self)

2624        3
2625

2650    def __getitem__(self, key: int):
2651        """
2652        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence.
2653
2654        Example 1:
2655        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
2656        >>> it(lst)[1]
2657        2
2658
2659        Example 2:
2660        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
2661        >>> it(lst)[3]
2662        Traceback (most recent call last):
2663        ...
2664        IndexError: Index 3 out of range
2665        """
2666        return self.element_at(key)

2668    @overload
2669    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2670        ...
2671    @overload
2672    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2673        ...
2674    @overload
2675    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2676        ...
2677    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[..., R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2678        if hasattr(callback, '__code__'):
2679            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 2:
2680                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2681                return lambda x: callback(x, index()) 
2682            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 3:
2683                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2684                return lambda x: callback(x, index(), self)
2685        return callback
2686
2687
2688class AutoIncrementIndex:
2689    idx = 0
2690    def __call__(self) -> int:
2691        val = self.idx
2692        self.idx += 1
2693        return val

2696class SequenceTransform(Generic[IterableS, T], Iterable[T]):
2697    _iter: IterableS
2698    _cache: Optional[List[T]]
2699
2700    def __init__(self, iterable: IterableS) -> None:
2701        super().__init__()
2702        self._iter = iterable
2703        self._cache = None
2704    
2705    def __iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2706        if self._cache:
2707            yield from self._cache
2708        else:
2709            cache: List[T] = []
2710            for x in self.__do_iter__():
2711                cache.append(x)
2712                yield x
2713            self._cache = cache
2714
2715    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T] :
2716        yield from self._iter
2717
2718    def __len__(self) -> int:
2719        if not isinstance(self._iter, SequenceTransform):
2720            # not Sequence, just a wrapper of List, Tuple.etc.
2721            # we can get lenght of it directly.
2722            if hasattr(self._iter, '__len__'):
2723                return len(self._iter) # type: ignore
2724            elif hasattr(self._iter, '__length_hint__'):
2725                return self._iter.__length_hint__() # type: ignore
2726        # we need iterate all to get length
2727        cache = self._cache
2728        if cache is None:
2729            for _ in self:
2730                pass
2731            cache = self._cache
2732        if cache is not None:
2733            return len(cache)
2734        return 0
2735
2736    def as_sequence(self) -> Sequence[T]:
2737        return it(self)
2738

2740class FilteringTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2741    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> None:
2742        super().__init__(iterable)
2743        self._predicate = predicate
2744    
2745    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2746        for i in self._iter:
2747            if self._predicate(i):
2748                yield i

2751class MappingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], R]):
2752    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], transform: Callable[[T], R]) -> None:
2753        super().__init__(iterable)
2754        self._transform = transform
2755    
2756    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[R]:
2757        for i in self._iter:
2758            yield self._transform(i)

2760
2761class ParallelMappingTransform(SequenceTransform[Sequence[T], R]):
2762    Executor = Literal['Thread', 'Process']
2763
2764    def __init__(
2765            self, 
2766            iterable: Sequence[T], 
2767            transformer: Callable[[T], R], 
2768            max_workers: Optional[int]=None, 
2769            chunksize: int=1,
2770            executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor = 'Thread') -> None:
2771
2772        super().__init__(iterable)
2773        self._transformer = transformer
2774        self._max_workers = max_workers
2775        self._executor = executor
2776        self._chunksize = chunksize
2777    
2778    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[R]:
2779        import os
2780
2781        def create_executor(max_workers: int):
2782            if self._executor == 'Process':
2783                from concurrent.futures import ProcessPoolExecutor
2784                return ProcessPoolExecutor(max_workers=max_workers)
2785            else:
2786                from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
2787                return ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=max_workers, thread_name_prefix='PyIter worker')
2788
2789        chunksize = self._chunksize
2790        max_workers = self._max_workers or min(32, (os.cpu_count() or 1) + 4)
2791        batch_size = max_workers * chunksize
2792        
2793        for batch in self._iter.chunked(batch_size):
2794            with create_executor(max_workers) as executor:
2795                yield from executor.map(self._transformer, batch, chunksize=chunksize)
2796

2816class DropTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):

2818        super().__init__(iterable)
2819        self._n = n

2828class DropWhileTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2829    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> None:
2830        super().__init__(iterable)
2831        self._predicate = predicate
2832    
2833    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2834        drop_state = True
2835        for e in self._iter:
2836            if drop_state and self._predicate(e):
2837                continue
2838            else:
2839                drop_state = False
2840            yield e

2855class TakeWhileTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2856    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> None:
2857        super().__init__(iterable)
2858        self._predicate = predicate
2859

2861        take_state = True
2862        for e in self._iter:

2869class MergingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], V]):
2870    def __init__(self, 
2871        iterable: Iterable[T], 
2872        other: Iterable[R],
2873        transformer: Callable[[T, R], V] = lambda a,b:(a,b)
2874    ) -> None:
2875        super().__init__(iterable)
2876        self._other = other
2877        self._transformer = transformer
2878    
2879    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[V]:
2880        iter1 = iter(self._iter)
2881        iter2 = iter(self._other)
2882        while True:
2883            try:
2884                yield self._transformer(next(iter1), next(iter2))
2885            except StopIteration:
2886                break
2887
2888
2889class IntersectionTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[Iterable[T]], T]):
2890    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[Iterable[T]]) -> None:
2891        super().__init__(iterable)
2892    
2893    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2894        iters = it(self._iter)
2895        seen: Set[T] = set()
2896        for v in iters.first():
2897            if v not in seen and iters.all(lambda iter: v in iter):
2898                yield v
2899                seen.add(v)
2900
2901
2902class MergingWithNextTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], V]):
2903    def __init__(self, 
2904    iterable: Iterable[T], 
2905    transformer: Callable[[T, T], V] = lambda a,b:(a,b)) -> None:
2906        super().__init__(iterable)
2907        self._transformer = transformer
2908    
2909    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[V]:
2910        it = iter(self._iter)
2911        try:
2912            c = next(it)
2913            while True:
2914                n = next(it)
2915                yield self._transformer(c, n)
2916                c = n
2917        except StopIteration:
2918            pass

2920
2921class DistinctTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2922    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], key_selector: Optional[Callable[[T], Any]]=None) -> None:
2923        super().__init__(iterable)
2924        self._key_selector = key_selector
2925    
2926    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2927        seen: Set[Any] = set()
2928        for e in self._iter:
2929            k = self._key_selector(e) if self._key_selector else e
2930            if k not in seen:
2931                seen.add(k)
2932                yield e

2935class Grouping(NamedTuple, Generic[K, T]):
2936    key: K
2937    values: Sequence[T]
2938
2939
2940class GroupingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], Grouping[K, T]]):
2941    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], key_func: Callable[[T], K]) -> None:
2942        super().__init__(iterable)
2943        self._key_func = key_func
2944    
2945    @property
2946    def keys(self) -> Sequence[K]:
2947        return it(self).map(lambda x: x.key)
2948    
2949    @property
2950    def values(self) -> Sequence[Sequence[T]]:
2951        return it(self).map(lambda x: x.values)
2952    
2953    @property
2954    def items(self) -> Sequence[Grouping[K, T]]:
2955        return it(self)
2956    
2957    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[Grouping[K, T]]:
2958        from collections import defaultdict
2959        d: DefaultDict[K, List[T]] = defaultdict(list)
2960        for e in self._iter:
2961            d[self._key_func(e)].append(e)
2962        yield from it(d.items()).map(lambda x: Grouping(x[0], it(x[1])))
2963

2965class CombinationTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], Tuple[T, ...]]):
2966    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], n: int) -> None:
2967        super().__init__(iterable)
2968        self._n = n
2969    
2970    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[Tuple[T, ...]]:
2971        from itertools import combinations
2972        yield from combinations(self._iter, self._n)

2974
2975class WindowedTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], List[T]]):
2976    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], size: int, step: int, partialWindows :bool) -> None:
2977        super().__init__(iterable)
2978        self._size = size
2979        self._step = step
2980        self._partialWindows = partialWindows
2981    
2982    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[List[T]]:
2983        from collections import deque
2984        window: Deque[T] = deque(maxlen=self._size)
2985        for e in self._iter:
2986            window.append(e)
2987            if len(window) == self._size:
2988                yield list(window)
2989            if len(window) == self._size:
2990                for _ in range(self._step):
2991                    window.popleft()
2992        
2993        if self._partialWindows and len(window) > 0:
2994            yield list(window)
2995

2997class ConcatTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[Iterable[T]], T]):
2998    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[Iterable[T]]) -> None:
2999        super().__init__(iterable)
3000    
3001    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
3002        for i in self._iter:
3003            yield from i

3006class ShufflingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
3007    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], random: Optional[Union[Random, str, int]]=None) -> None:
3008        super().__init__(iterable)
3009        if random is None or isinstance(random, (str, int)):
3010            from random import Random
3011            self._random = Random(random)
3012        else:
3013            self._random = random
3014    
3015    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
3016        lst = list(self._iter)
3017        self._random.shuffle(lst)
3018        yield from lst

3021class ProgressTransform(SequenceTransform[Sequence[T], T]):
3022    def __init__(self, iterable: Sequence[T], progress_func: Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]]) -> None:
3023        super().__init__(iterable)
3024        self._progress_func = progress_func
3025    
3026    @property
3027    def len(self) -> int:
3028        return len(self._iter)
3029    
3030    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
3031        yield from self._progress_func(self._iter)

3037    #             super().__init__(iterable)

3055class SequenceProducer:
3056    @overload
3057    def __call__(self, elements: List[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
3058        ...
3059    @overload
3060    def __call__(self, elements: Iterable[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
3061        ...
3062    @overload
3063    def __call__(self, *elements: T) -> Sequence[T]:
3064        ...
3065    def __call__(self, *iterable: Union[Iterable[T], List[T], T]) -> Sequence[T]: # type: ignore
3066        if len(iterable) == 1:
3067            iter = iterable[0]
3068            if isinstance(iter, Sequence):
3069                return iter # type: ignore
3070            if isinstance(iter, Iterable) and not isinstance(iter, str):
3071                return Sequence(iter) # type: ignore
3072        return Sequence(iterable) # type: ignore
3073    
3074    def json(self, filepath: str, **kwargs: Dict[str, Any]) -> Sequence[Any]:
3075        """
3076        Reads and parses the input of a json file.
3077        """
3078        import json
3079        with open(filepath, 'r') as f:
3080            data = json.load(f, **kwargs) # type: ignore
3081            return self(data)
3082    
3083    def csv(self, filepath: str):
3084        """
3085        Reads and parses the input of a csv file.
3086        """
3087        return self.read_csv(filepath)
3088
3089    def read_csv(self, filepath: str, header: Optional[int]=0):
3090        """
3091        Reads and parses the input of a csv file.
3092
3093        Example 1:
3094        >>> it.read_csv('tests/data/a.csv')
3095        [{'a': 'a1', 'b': '1'}, {'a': 'a2', 'b': '2'}]
3096        """
3097        import csv
3098        it = self
3099        with open(filepath) as f:
3100            reader = csv.reader(f)
3101            iter = it(*reader)
3102            if header is None or header < 0:
3103                return iter
3104
3105            headers = iter.element_at_or_none(header)
3106            if headers is not None:
3107                if header == 0:
3108                    iter = iter.skip(1)
3109                else:
3110                    iter = iter.filter(lambda _, i: i != header)
3111
3112                return iter.map(lambda row: it(row).associate_by(
3113                    lambda _, ordinal: headers[ordinal] if ordinal < len(headers) else f'undefined_{ordinal}')
3114                )
3115            return iter

class Sequence(typing.Generic[~T], typing.Iterable[~T]): 
  31class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  32    """
  33    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  34    provided by that function.
  35    
  36    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  37    """
  38    _iter: SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]
  39
  40    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T]) -> None:
  41        super().__init__()
  42        self._iter = SequenceTransform(iterable)
  43

  45    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  46        ...

  52        ...
  53    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  54        """
  55        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
  56
  57        Example 1:
  58        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  59        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
  60        ['a1', 'a2']
  61
  62        Example 2:
  63        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  64        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
  65        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
  66        """
  67        return FilteringTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)).as_sequence()
  68
  69    @deprecated("use `.filter(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.", category=None)
  70    def filter_indexed(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  71        return self.filter(predicate)
  72
  73    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
  74        """
  75        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
  76
  77        Example 1:
  78        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
  79        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
  80        [1, 3]
  81
  82        """
  83        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ)) # type: ignore

  94    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  95        """
  96        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
  97
  98        Example 1:
  99        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 100        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 101        ['b1', 'b2']
 102
 103        Example 2:
 104        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 105        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 106        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 107        """
 108        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 109        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))

 137    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 138        """
 139        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 140        to each element in the original Sequence.
 141
 142        Example 1:
 143        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 144        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 145        [12, 13]
 146
 147        Example 2:
 148        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 149        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 150        ['A0', 'B1']
 151
 152        Example 3:
 153        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 154        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 155        [2, 3]
 156        """
 157        return MappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)).as_sequence()
 158

 160    def map_indexed(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 161        return self.map(transform)

 171    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Awaitable[R]], return_exceptions: Literal[False] = False) -> Sequence[R]:
 172        ...
 173    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[..., Awaitable[R]], return_exceptions: bool = False):
 174        """
 175        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 176        """
 177        from asyncio import gather
 178        if return_exceptions:
 179            return it(await gather(*self.map(transform), return_exceptions=True))
 180        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform)))

 198        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()

 277    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 278        """
 279        Returns first element.
 280
 281        Example 1:
 282        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 283        >>> it(lst).first()
 284        'a'
 285
 286        Example 2:
 287        >>> lst = []
 288        >>> it(lst).first()
 289        Traceback (most recent call last):
 290        ...
 291        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 292
 293        Example 3:
 294        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 295        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 296        'b'
 297
 298        Example 4:
 299        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 300        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 301        Traceback (most recent call last):
 302        ...
 303        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 304
 305        Example 5:
 306        >>> lst = [None]
 307        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 308        True
 309        """
 310        for e in self:
 311            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 312                return e
 313        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")

 327    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[R]]] = None) -> R:
 328        """
 329        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 330
 331        Example 1:
 332        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 333        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 334        12
 335
 336        Example 2:
 337        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 338        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 339        Traceback (most recent call last):
 340        ...
 341        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 342        """
 343
 344        v = self.first_not_none_of_or_none() if transform is None else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 345        if v is None:
 346            raise ValueError('No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.')
 347        return v

 360        ...
 361    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 362        """
 363        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 364
 365        Example 1:
 366        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 367        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 368        12
 369
 370        Example 2:
 371        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 372        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 373        True
 374        """
 375        if transform is None:
 376            return self.first_or_none()
 377        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 391    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 392        """
 393        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 394
 395        Example 1:
 396        >>> lst = []
 397        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 398        True
 399
 400        Example 2:
 401        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 402        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 403        'a'
 404
 405        Example 2:
 406        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 407        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 408        'b'
 409        """
 410        return next(iter(self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate)), None)

 424        ...
 425    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], T], default: Optional[T] = None) -> T: # type: ignore
 426        """
 427        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 428
 429        Example 1:
 430        >>> lst = []
 431        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 432        'a'
 433
 434        Example 2:
 435        >>> lst = ['b']
 436        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 437        'b'
 438        
 439        Example 3:
 440        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 441        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 442        'b'
 443
 444        Example 4:
 445        >>> lst = []
 446        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 447        'd'
 448        """
 449        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 450            return none_or(self.first_or_none(predicate), default) # type: ignore
 451        else:
 452            default = predicate
 453        return none_or(self.first_or_none(), default)
 454
 455    @overload

 457        ...
 458    @overload

 460        ...

 462    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T:
 463        ...
 464    @overload
 465    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 466        ...
 467    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 468        """
 469        Returns last element.
 470
 471        Example 1:
 472        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 473        >>> it(lst).last()
 474        'c'
 475
 476        Example 2:
 477        >>> lst = []
 478        >>> it(lst).last()
 479        Traceback (most recent call last):
 480        ...
 481        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 482        """
 483        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 484        if v is None:
 485            raise ValueError('Sequence is empty.')
 486        return v
 487
 488    @overload
 489    def last_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 490        ...
 491    @overload
 492    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 493        ...
 494    @overload

 496        ...
 497    @overload
 498    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 499        ...
 500    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 501        """
 502        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 503
 504        Exmaple 1:
 505        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 506        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 507        'c'
 508
 509        Exmaple 2:
 510        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 511        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 512        'b'
 513
 514        Exmaple 3:
 515        >>> lst = []
 516        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 517        True
 518        """
 519        last: Optional[T] = None
 520        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 521            last = i
 522        return last

 524    def index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 525        """
 526        Returns first index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 527
 528        Example 1:
 529        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 530        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('b')
 531        1
 532
 533        Example 2:
 534        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 535        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('d')
 536        """
 537        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 538            if x == element:
 539                return i
 540        return None

 574    def index_of_or_else(self, element: T, f: Callable[[], int]) -> int:
 575        """
 576        Returns first index of [element], or computes the value from a callback if the collection does not contain element.
 577         
 578        Example 1:
 579        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 580        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_else('b', lambda: 2)
 581        1
 582

 590    def last_index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 591        """
 592         Returns last index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 593
 594        Example 1:
 595        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 596        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('b')
 597        3
 598
 599        Example 2:
 600        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 601        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('d')
 602        """
 603        seq = self.reversed()
 604        last_idx = len(seq) - 1
 605        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 606            if x == element:
 607                return last_idx - i
 608        return None

 683                return i

 896    @overload

 898        ...
 899    @overload
 900    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T:
 901        ...
 902    @overload
 903    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T:
 904        ...
 905    @overload
 906    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 907        ...
 908    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 909        """
 910        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
 911        or more than one matching element.
 912
 913        Exmaple 1:
 914        >>> lst = ['a']
 915        >>> it(lst).single()
 916        'a'
 917
 918        Exmaple 2:
 919        >>> lst = []
 920        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 921        Traceback (most recent call last):
 922        ...
 923        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
 924
 925        Exmaple 2:
 926        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 927        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 928        Traceback (most recent call last):
 929        ...
 930        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
 931        """
 932        single: Optional[T] = None
 933        found = False
 934        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 935            if found:
 936                raise ValueError('Sequence contains more than one matching element.')
 937            single = i
 938            found = True
 939        if single is None:
 940            raise ValueError('Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.')
 941        return single
 942
 943    @overload
 944    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 945        ...
 946    @overload
 947    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 948        ...
 949    @overload
 950    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 951        ...
 952    @overload
 953    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 954        ...
 955    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 956        """
 957        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
 958        or more than one element was found.
 959
 960        Exmaple 1:
 961        >>> lst = ['a']
 962        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 963        'a'
 964
 965        Exmaple 2:
 966        >>> lst = []
 967        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 968
 969        Exmaple 2:
 970        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 971        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 972
 973        """
 974        single: Optional[T] = None
 975        found = False
 976        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 977            if found:
 978                return None
 979            single = i
 980            found = True
 981        if not found:
 982            return None
 983        return single
